{"id":"2006.11805","submitter":"Russell Miller","authors":"Rachael Alvir, Wesley Calvert, Grant Goodman, Valentina Harizanov,\n  Julia Knight, Andrey Morozov, Russell Miller, Alexandra Soskova, and Rose\n  Weisshaar","title":"Interpreting a field in its Heisenberg group","comments":"Published online by the *Journal of Symbolic Logic*, 23 December\n  2021. Print version to appear subsequently","journal-ref":null,"doi":"10.1017/jsl.2021.107","report-no":null,"categories":"math.LO","license":"http://arxiv.org/licenses/nonexclusive-distrib/1.0/","abstract":"  We improve on and generalize a 1960 result of Maltsev. For a field $F$, we\ndenote by $H(F)$ the Heisenberg group with entries in $F$. Maltsev showed that\nthere is a copy of $F$ defined in $H(F)$, using existential formulas with an\narbitrary non-commuting pair $(u,v)$ as parameters. We show that $F$ is\ninterpreted in $H(F)$ using computable $\\Sigma_1$ formulas with no parameters.\nWe give two proofs. The first is an existence proof, relying on a result of\nHarrison-Trainor, Melnikov, R. Miller, and Montalb\\'an. This proof allows the\npossibility that the elements of $F$ are represented by tuples in $H(F)$ of no\nfixed arity. The second proof is direct, giving explicit finitary existential\nformulas that define the interpretation, with elements of $F$ represented by\ntriples in $H(F)$. Looking at what was used to arrive at this parameter-free\ninterpretation of $F$ in $H(F)$, we give general conditions sufficient to\neliminate parameters from interpretations.\n","versions":[{"version":"v1","created":"Sun, 21 Jun 2020 14:04:23 GMT"},{"version":"v2","created":"Tue, 5 Apr 2022 17:17:52 GMT"}],"update_date":"2022-04-06"}
